<p>We note that differentiating 
 <xref ref-type="disp-formula" rid="equ4">Equation 4</xref> with respect to time defines the equation governing the dynamics of population average susceptibility
 <disp-formula id="equ5">
  <label>(5)</label>
  <math id="m5">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mfrac>
      <mi>d</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>d</mi>
       <mo>⁢</mo>
       <mi>t</mi>
      </mrow>
     </mfrac>
     <mo>⁢</mo>
     <msub>
      <mi>S</mi>
      <mi>a</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mrow>
     <mo>-</mo>
     <mrow>
      <mi>ν</mi>
      <mo>⁢</mo>
      <msub>
       <mi>S</mi>
       <mi>a</mi>
      </msub>
      <mo>⁢</mo>
      <mrow>
       <munder>
        <mo largeop="true" movablelimits="false" symmetric="true">∑</mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
       </munder>
       <mrow>
        <msub>
         <mi>K</mi>
         <mrow>
          <mi>a</mi>
          <mo>⁢</mo>
          <mi>b</mi>
         </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>⁢</mo>
        <msub>
         <mi>I</mi>
         <mi>b</mi>
        </msub>
       </mrow>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>which is exactly the same as the dynamics of susceptibility in 
 <xref rid="bib14" ref-type="bibr">Gog and Grenfell (2002)</xref> and 
 <xref rid="bib29" ref-type="bibr">Luksza and Lässig (2014)</xref> in the limit of negligible population turnover 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="inf29">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>γ</mi>
     <mo>/</mo>
     <mi>ν</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mo>≪</mo>
    <mn>1</mn>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>.
</p>
